# Question 2

Overall mortality indicators (e.g., life expectancy at birth or survival to a given age) are important indicators of health status in a country. Because data on the incidence and prevalence of diseases are frequently unavailable, mortality rates are often used to identify vulnerable populations. They are also one of the most frequently used indicators for comparing socioeconomic development across countries.

The data in this problem is from the United Nations Population Division and contain the following variables for 208 countries: 

* `LifeExpectancy_2022`: the life expectancy at birth in the year 2022 (number of years a newborn infant would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of its birth were to stay the same throughout its life);

* `IncomeGroup`: the country's income group, coded as: low, lower-middle, upper-middle, and high.

**Data source and description**: \href{https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.LE00.IN}{\textcolor{blue}{https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.LE00.IN}}

